## The Memory Leak: Root Cause Analysis

This component has **three** compounding problems, two of which are major leaks.

### Issue 1 — No cleanup function in `useEffect`

The effect calls `window.addEventListener(...)` but never returns a cleanup function to call `removeEventListener(...)`. When the component unmounts (you navigate away), the listeners stay attached to the global `window` object forever. The component's DOM is gone, but the closures — and everything they reference (the `setScrollY`, `setScrollDirection` setters, the React fiber) — are kept alive by `window`'s listener list, so they can never be garbage collected.

### Issue 2 — Missing dependency array

`useEffect` with **no second argument runs after *every* render**. Every time `scrollY`, `scrollDirection`, or `lastScrollY` changes — i.e. on *every scroll event* — the component re-renders, the effect runs again, and **two more listeners get added**. With no cleanup, you don't just leak once per page visit; you leak on every single scroll tick. Scrolling a page once can attach hundreds of duplicate handlers.

### Issue 3 — Stale closure bug (functional correctness)

Because the handler closes over `lastScrollY` from render, and there's no proper dependency handling, the direction logic reads a stale value. The correct fix is to compute direction from the previous value using the functional setter form, so we don't need `lastScrollY` in state at all.

### Why the two issues compound (the lifecycle)

1. Mount → effect runs → 2 listeners attached.
2. User scrolls → handler fires → 3 state updates → re-render.
3. No dependency array → effect runs again → 2 **more** listeners attached (old ones never removed).
4. Repeat per scroll event → unbounded growth.
5. Navigate away → unmount → no cleanup → **all** accumulated listeners survive on `window`.
6. Navigate back → fresh mount starts the whole accumulation again on top of the orphaned ones.

This is exactly the "increasingly slow and laggy after navigating back and forth" symptom: each visit leaves behind a growing pile of live closures that the GC cannot reclaim, and each surviving handler still runs on every scroll/resize, so CPU cost climbs too.

### Why anonymous arrow functions break cleanup

`removeEventListener(event, handler)` removes a listener **only if you pass the exact same function reference** that was registered. An inline arrow function creates a *brand-new function object every time the effect runs* — so even if you added a cleanup, you'd have no reference to the function you originally attached, and `removeEventListener` would silently match nothing. You **must** name the handler (or store it in a stable variable) so the same reference is used for both add and remove.

### React 18 Strict Mode makes this loud in development

In development, React 18 Strict Mode intentionally **mounts → unmounts → remounts** every component and **double-invokes effects**. A correctly-cleaned effect is invisible under this (add → remove → add). But this buggy version, with no cleanup, immediately attaches duplicate listeners on the very first mount, so the bug surfaces during development instead of only in production. It's a built-in detector for exactly this class of missing-cleanup mistake.

---

## Corrected Component

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function ScrollTracker() {
    const [scrollY, setScrollY] = useState(0);
    const [scrollDirection, setScrollDirection] = useState('none');

    useEffect(() => {
        // Named handlers → stable references usable by both add and remove.
        function handleScroll() {
            const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;

            // Functional update avoids a stale `lastScrollY` closure and
            // removes the need to keep it in state at all.
            setScrollY((prevScrollY) => {
                setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > prevScrollY ? 'down' : 'up');
                return currentScrollY;
            });
        }

        function handleResize() {
            console.log('Window resized, recalculating...');
            setScrollY(window.scrollY);
        }

        window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
        window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

        // Cleanup: removes the SAME references on unmount / before re-run.
        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
            window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
        };
    }, []); // Empty array → effect runs once on mount, cleans up once on unmount.

    return (
        <div style={{ position: 'fixed', top: 10, right: 10, padding: '10px', background: '#333', color: '#fff' }}>
            <p>Scroll Y: {scrollY}</p>
            <p>Direction: {scrollDirection}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default ScrollTracker;
```

### What changed and why it's still equivalent

| Fix | Effect |
|-----|--------|
| **Empty dependency array `[]`** | Effect runs once on mount, not on every render — no per-scroll re-subscription. |
| **`return () => { removeEventListener(...) }`** | Listeners are torn down on unmount, so nothing survives navigation. |
| **Named `handleScroll` / `handleResize`** | Same function reference passed to add and remove, so cleanup actually works. |
| **Functional `setScrollY((prev) => ...)`** | Direction is computed against the true previous value with no stale closure, so `lastScrollY` state is no longer needed and the empty dep array stays valid (no `lastScrollY` dependency to track). |

Functionality is preserved exactly: it still displays the live scroll position, still reports `'up'`/`'down'` direction, and still logs and updates on resize — but now with a single, properly cleaned-up subscription. Under Strict Mode you'll see add → remove → add on first mount, confirming the cleanup path works.

One subtlety worth noting: the original set direction inside the `scroll` handler only; I kept that behavior. If you wanted resize to also recompute direction, the functional-update pattern above would let you do it cleanly — but I left it matching the original to keep behavior identical.

